<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>OpenClaw Operational Manual - Complete Edition</title>
    <style>
        :root {
            --primary: #00f0ff; /* Arc Reactor Blue */
            --secondary: #0a192f;
            --bg-dark: #020c1b;
            --text: #e6f1ff;
            --accent: #ff003c;
            --dim: #8892b0;
            --glass: rgba(10, 25, 47, 0.95);
            --success: #64ffda;
            --border: rgba(0, 240, 255, 0.2);
        }
        body {
            background-color: var(--bg-dark);
            color: var(--text);
            font-family: 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            display: flex;
            height: 100vh;
            overflow: hidden;
        }
        
        /* Sidebar Navigation */
        #sidebar {
            width: 350px;
            background: var(--secondary);
            border-right: 1px solid var(--primary);
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            padding: 0;
            box-shadow: 2px 0 15px rgba(0, 240, 255, 0.1);
            overflow: hidden; /* Manage internal scroll */
        }
        
        #sidebar-header {
            padding: 20px;
            border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
            text-align: center;
        }
        
        #sidebar-header h2 {
            color: var(--primary);
            text-transform: uppercase;
            letter-spacing: 2px;
            font-size: 1.2rem;
            margin: 0;
        }
        
        #search-box {
            margin-top: 15px;
            width: 100%;
            padding: 8px;
            background: rgba(0,0,0,0.3);
            border: 1px solid var(--dim);
            color: var(--text);
            border-radius: 4px;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }
        
        #nav-list {
            flex: 1;
            overflow-y: auto;
            padding: 10px;
        }

        .nav-category {
            font-size: 0.8rem;
            text-transform: uppercase;
            color: var(--accent);
            margin-top: 20px;
            margin-bottom: 5px;
            padding-left: 10px;
            font-weight: bold;
            letter-spacing: 1px;
        }
        
        .nav-item {
            padding: 8px 15px;
            margin-bottom: 2px;
            cursor: pointer;
            border-radius: 4px;
            transition: all 0.2s;
            color: var(--dim);
            font-size: 0.9rem;
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
        }
        .nav-item:hover {
            background: rgba(0, 240, 255, 0.05);
            color: var(--text);
        }
        .nav-item.active {
            background: rgba(0, 240, 255, 0.15);
            color: var(--primary);
            border-left: 3px solid var(--primary);
        }
        
        /* Main Content Area */
        #main {
            flex: 1;
            padding: 40px 60px;
            overflow-y: auto;
            position: relative;
            background: radial-gradient(circle at top right, rgba(0, 240, 255, 0.05), transparent 40%);
            scroll-behavior: smooth;
        }
        
        /* Typography */
        h1 { font-size: 2.5rem; color: var(--primary); margin-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(0, 240, 255, 0.3); padding-bottom: 15px; }
        h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; color: var(--text); margin-top: 40px; margin-bottom: 20px; }
        h3 { color: var(--success); margin-top: 30px; font-size: 1.4rem; border-left: 4px solid var(--accent); padding-left: 15px; }
        h4 { color: var(--dim); margin-top: 20px; font-size: 1.1rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 1px; }
        
        p, li { 
            line-height: 1.7; 
            color: #bdc5dd; 
            font-size: 1.05rem; 
            max-width: 900px; 
            margin-bottom: 15px;
        }
        ul { margin-left: 20px; }
        
        strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 700; }
        
        /* Components */
        .card {
            background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.03);
            border: 1px solid var(--border);
            border-radius: 6px;
            padding: 25px;
            margin: 25px 0;
            max-width: 900px;
        }
        .card-title { color: var(--primary); font-weight: bold; font-size: 1.1rem; margin-bottom: 15px; display: block; }
        
        .code-block {
            background: #000;
            border: 1px solid var(--dim);
            padding: 15px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            font-family: 'Courier New', monospace;
            color: var(--success);
            overflow-x: auto;
            margin: 15px 0;
            position: relative;
        }
        
        .copy-btn {
            position: absolute;
            top: 5px;
            right: 5px;
            background: #333;
            border: none;
            color: #fff;
            padding: 5px 10px;
            border-radius: 3px;
            cursor: pointer;
            font-size: 0.8rem;
        }
        .copy-btn:hover { background: var(--primary); color: #000; }

        .analogy-box {
            background: rgba(0, 255, 0, 0.05);
            border-left: 4px solid var(--success);
            padding: 20px;
            margin: 20px 0;
            font-style: italic;
            color: #d0ffd0;
            max-width: 900px;
        }

        .warning-box {
            background: rgba(255, 0, 0, 0.05);
            border-left: 4px solid var(--accent);
            padding: 20px;
            margin: 20px 0;
            color: #ffd0d0;
            max-width: 900px;
        }

        /* Responsive Table */
        table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 20px; max-width: 900px; }
        th, td { text-align: left; padding: 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--dim); }
        th { color: var(--primary); }
        
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <div id="sidebar">
        <div id="sidebar-header">
            <h2>J.O.T.I. Ultimate</h2>
            <input type="text" id="search-box" placeholder="Search Manual..." onkeyup="filterNav()">
        </div>
        <div id="nav-list">
            <!-- Nav populated by JS -->
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="main">
        <!-- Content injects here -->
    </div>

    <script>
        // --- COMPLETE MANUAL DATA ---
        // Storing the entire manual text structured by chapter.
        const manualData = [
            {
                id: "intro",
                title: "1. What Is OpenClaw?",
                content: `
                    <h1>1. What Is OpenClaw?</h1>
                    <p>OpenClaw is a free, open-source AI agent — a piece of software that runs continuously on your computer and performs tasks on your behalf, including while you sleep. Unlike a regular chatbot (such as ChatGPT) where you type a question and receive an answer, OpenClaw is proactive: it monitors your environment, schedules its own tasks, takes actions, builds tools, remembers everything you tell it, and operates as if it were a full-time digital employee working around the clock.</p>
                    <p>The term "AI agent" refers to a program that can make decisions and take actions in pursuit of a goal, rather than just responding passively to questions. OpenClaw is one of the most capable examples of this type of software available to the public today.</p>
                    
                    <h3>1.1 Core Capabilities</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Controls your computer:</strong> OpenClaw can open applications, navigate your file system, use your web browser, click buttons, and interact with software just as a human would.</li>
                        <li><strong>Browses the internet:</strong> It can open web pages, read news, research topics, scroll through social media feeds (such as Twitter/X), and find trending content.</li>
                        <li><strong>Writes and runs code:</strong> It can create fully functioning software applications, websites, and scripts entirely on your behalf — no coding experience required.</li>
                        <li><strong>Manages files and apps:</strong> It can read, write, and organize files, interact with to-do list apps, calendar apps, and project management platforms.</li>
                        <li><strong>Communicates with you via messaging:</strong> Rather than requiring you to open a special app, OpenClaw communicates through messaging platforms you already use daily, such as Telegram, iMessage, or Discord.</li>
                        <li><strong>Remembers everything:</strong> Every detail you share — your preferences, goals, career background, personal life — is stored in memory and recalled in every future conversation.</li>
                        <li><strong>Self-improves:</strong> When it makes a mistake or lacks a capability, you can instruct it to analyze the problem and build a new "skill" to handle it better going forward.</li>
                        <li><strong>Schedules its own tasks:</strong> Using a system called "cron jobs" (automated scheduled tasks), it can perform actions at specific times every day, week, or at any interval you define, without any further input from you.</li>
                        <li><strong>Acts proactively:</strong> It will notice opportunities — such as a trending news story or a business opportunity — and take action on your behalf, reporting results back to you.</li>
                    </ul>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "hosting",
                title: "2. Hosting: Local vs. VPS",
                content: `
                    <h1>2. Where to Host OpenClaw</h1>
                    <p>Before installing OpenClaw, you must decide where it will run. There are two options: locally (on a physical device you own) or on a VPS (Virtual Private Server). Understanding the difference is critical.</p>

                    <h3>2.1 Option A: Running Locally (Strongly Recommended)</h3>
                    <p>"Locally" means OpenClaw runs on a physical computer that is in your home or office. This is the strongly recommended approach.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Security by default:</strong> A local machine is not exposed to the public internet by default, which means hackers and bad actors cannot easily access it.</li>
                        <li><strong>Direct integration with your life:</strong> Your local computer is already logged into all your accounts — email, social media, apps, calendars. OpenClaw can use all of these immediately.</li>
                        <li><strong>Visibility and usability:</strong> You can watch OpenClaw work in real time on your screen.</li>
                        <li><strong>Full power:</strong> Experts estimate you get roughly 80% less value from running OpenClaw on a VPS compared to locally.</li>
                        <li><strong>Free to start:</strong> No server fees.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>2.2 Option B: Running on a VPS (Not Recommended)</h3>
                    <div class="warning-box">
                        <strong>Warning:</strong> Unless you are an experienced system administrator, avoid this.
                    </div>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Security is your responsibility:</strong> By default, a VPS is exposed to the internet. You must manually configure firewalls and SSH keys.</li>
                        <li><strong>No native integrations:</strong> The VPS does not have your accounts, apps, or files. Every integration must be manually set up.</li>
                        <li><strong>Harder to supervise:</strong> Requires using a remote terminal.</li>
                        <li><strong>Ongoing cost:</strong> Monthly fees apply.</li>
                    </ul>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "hardware",
                title: "3. Hardware Requirements",
                content: `
                    <h1>3. Hardware: What Device Should You Use?</h1>
                    <p>One of the most common misconceptions about OpenClaw is that it requires expensive hardware. This is not true — at least to get started.</p>

                    <h3>3.1 Start with What You Already Have</h3>
                    <p>You can run OpenClaw on virtually any computer you already own, including:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>An old or spare laptop.</li>
                        <li>A Raspberry Pi (inexpensive single-board computer).</li>
                        <li>Your current primary desktop or laptop.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>3.2 The Mac Mini — Best Value</h3>
                    <div class="card">
                        <span class="card-title">Recommendation: Mac Mini (M-Series)</span>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Price:</strong> ~$600 base model.</li>
                            <li><strong>Performance:</strong> Exceptional for AI tasks due to Apple Silicon.</li>
                            <li><strong>Energy:</strong> Runs cool and quietly for 24/7 operation.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <h3>3.3 Mac Studio — For Advanced Users</h3>
                    <p>Only necessary if you intend to run large <strong>Local AI Models</strong> (see Section 8). For most users starting out, this is overkill.</p>

                    <h3>3.4 Upgrade Path</h3>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Step 1: Use your current computer.</li>
                        <li>Step 2: Upgrade to Mac Mini ($600) for a dedicated agent machine.</li>
                        <li>Step 3: Upgrade to Mac Studio ($2000+) for heavy local model usage.</li>
                    </ol>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "install",
                title: "4. Installation & Onboarding",
                content: `
                    <h1>4. Installing OpenClaw</h1>
                    
                    <h3>4.1 The Command</h3>
                    <p>Visit openclaw.ai to copy the Quick Start command. Paste it into your terminal.</p>
                    <div class="code-block">
                        curl -sL https://openclaw.ai/install | bash
                        <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyText('curl -sL https://openclaw.ai/install | bash')">Copy</button>
                    </div>

                    <h1>5. Onboarding Configuration</h1>
                    <p>After installation, the interactive setup begins.</p>

                    <h3>5.3 Selecting Your AI Model ("Brain")</h3>
                    <p>This is the "Brain" of your agent. Options:</p>
                    <table>
                        <tr><th>Provider</th><th>Model</th><th>Cost</th><th>Best For</th></tr>
                        <tr><td>Anthropic</td><td>Claude Opus</td><td>~$200/mo</td><td>Complex reasoning, warmest personality.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Anthropic</td><td>Claude Sonnet</td><td>~$40/mo</td><td><strong>Best Value.</strong> Nearly as smart as Opus, 5x cheaper.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>OpenAI</td><td>GPT-4</td><td>Varies</td><td>If you already have a subscription.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>MiniMax</td><td>MiniMax 2.5</td><td>~$10/mo</td><td>Budget option.</td></tr>
                    </table>

                    <h3>5.5 Messaging Service</h3>
                    <p><strong>Recommendation: Telegram.</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Threading support makes long answers readable.</li>
                        <li>Slash commands (/reset, /kill) work natively.</li>
                        <li>Keeps agent chats separate from personal texts (iMessage).</li>
                    </ul>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "first_steps",
                title: "6. First Things After Setup",
                content: `
                    <h1>6. First Things to Do After Setup</h1>
                    <p>Do not skip this. These steps differentiate a proactive agent from a passive bot.</p>

                    <h3>6.1 The Brain Dump</h3>
                    <p>Think of OpenClaw as a new employee. You must introduce yourself.</p>
                    <div class="analogy-box">
                        <strong>Action:</strong> Send a detailed message covering:
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Background:</strong> "I am a [Job Title]. I specialize in [Skill]."</li>
                            <li><strong>Preferences:</strong> "Be concise. Don't ask permission for small tasks."</li>
                            <li><strong>Goals:</strong> "I want to grow my business to $10k MRR in 6 months."</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <h3>6.2 Set Up Your Morning Brief</h3>
                    <p>Your first automation. Copy this prompt:</p>
                    <div class="code-block">
                        Please schedule a brief for me every day at 8 a.m. Send it to my Telegram. I want the brief to include: 
                        1) The weather. 
                        2) Top news stories related to [MY INDUSTRY]. 
                        3) Any tasks on my to-do list. 
                        4) Tasks you can complete for me today that bring me closer to my goals.
                        <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyText(this.parentNode.innerText.replace('Copy', ''))">Copy</button>
                    </div>
                    <p>Item #4 enables "Reverse Prompting" — giving the agent permission to think for you.</p>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "brains_muscles",
                title: "7. Brains and Muscles",
                content: `
                    <h1>7. Brains and Muscles</h1>
                    <p>The framework for cost-effective intelligence.</p>

                    <h3>7.1 The Brain</h3>
                    <p>Your main model (Claude/GPT). Handles planning, reasoning, and conversation. It is expensive and smart.</p>

                    <h3>7.2 The Muscles</h3>
                    <p>Specialized, cheaper tools for specific tasks. Do not waste the Brain's time on these.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Coding:</strong> Codex CLI (OpenAI). Fast and optimized for code.</li>
                        <li><strong>News/Social:</strong> X API (Grok). Connected to real-time social data.</li>
                        <li><strong>Search:</strong> Brave Search API. Fast, cheap web indexing.</li>
                        <li><strong>Vision:</strong> Nano Banana. AI Image generation.</li>
                        <li><strong>Transcripts:</strong> Super Data API. Extracts text from YouTube videos.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>7.3 How to Set Up a Muscle</h3>
                    <p>Just ask: <em>"For coding tasks going forward, please use the Codex CLI."</em> The agent will handle the API key setup.</p>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "local_ai",
                title: "8. Local AI Models",
                content: `
                    <h1>8. Local AI Models</h1>
                    <p>Advanced topic. Running the "Brain" on your own hardware instead of the cloud.</p>
                    
                    <h3>8.2 Benefits</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Cost:</strong> Free (after hardware purchase). No per-token fees.</li>
                        <li><strong>Privacy:</strong> Data never leaves your device.</li>
                        <li><strong>Offline:</strong> Works without internet.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>8.4 How to Run</h3>
                    <p>Use <strong>Ollama</strong>. It makes downloading models (Llama 3, Mistral, etc.) simple.</p>
                    <p><em>Note: Requires powerful hardware (Mac Studio / M-Series Chips with high RAM).</em></p>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "skills",
                title: "9. Skills",
                content: `
                    <h1>9. OpenClaw Skills</h1>
                    <p>A "Skill" is a configuration file that teaches your agent how to use a specific tool.</p>

                    <h3>9.4 The Seven Most Useful Skills</h3>
                    <ol>
                        <li><strong>Notion:</strong> Read/Write notes, organize projects.</li>
                        <li><strong>Video Transcript Extractor (Super Data):</strong> Read YouTube videos as text.</li>
                        <li><strong>Typefully:</strong> Draft and schedule Twitter/X posts.</li>
                        <li><strong>Linear:</strong> Project management for software teams.</li>
                        <li><strong>Nano Banana:</strong> AI Image generation.</li>
                        <li><strong>SERP API:</strong> Google Images and YouTube Search.</li>
                        <li><strong>Last 30 Days:</strong> (Community Skill) Search Reddit/X for trends over the last month.</li>
                    </ol>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "use_cases",
                title: "10. Use Cases",
                content: `
                    <h1>10. Use Cases</h1>
                    <p>Real-world examples of what you can actually do.</p>

                    <h3>10.1 Second Brain</h3>
                    <p>Text your agent: <em>"Remember this: [Idea]"</em>. Later, ask it to recall ideas about that topic.
                    <br><strong>Advanced:</strong> Ask it to build a Next.js dashboard to visualize your memories.</p>

                    <h3>10.3 Content Factory</h3>
                    <p>Automated pipeline:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Agent A (Research) finds trending news.</li>
                        <li>Agent B (Writer) drafts scripts.</li>
                        <li>Agent C (Visuals) makes thumbnails.</li>
                        <li>You review the "Approvals" channel.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>10.5 Autonomous Task Generation</h3>
                    <p>Ask: <em>"Every morning, come up with 5 tasks you can do to bring me closer to my goals. Then do them."</em></p>

                    <h3>10.6 Mission Control</h3>
                    <p>Ask: <em>"Build me a custom dashboard in Next.js hosted locally. This will be our Mission Control."</em> Then add tools to it iteratively (Task tracker, Calendar, etc.).</p>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "mindset",
                title: "11. The OpenClaw Mindset",
                content: `
                    <h1>11. Communicating Effectively</h1>
                    
                    <h3>11.1 Employee, Not Tool</h3>
                    <p>Correct mental model: You are the Manager. OpenClaw is the Employee. Don't micro-manage steps; manage outcomes.</p>

                    <h3>11.2 End-State Goals</h3>
                    <p>❌ "Go to config and change heartbeat to 5 mins."<br>
                    ✅ "I want you to check for tasks every 5 mins instead of 30. Make that change."</p>

                    <h3>11.3 Reverse Prompting (CRITICAL)</h3>
                    <p>The most important technique. Ask the agent what IT thinks you should do.</p>
                    <div class="analogy-box">
                        "Based on my goals, what should we work on this week?"
                        <br>"What tools could we add to Mission Control to be more efficient?"
                    </div>
                `
            },
            {
                id: "security",
                title: "13. Security Protocols",
                content: `
                    <h1>13. Security — Staying Safe</h1>
                    <p>OpenClaw has Admin Access. Be thoughtful.</p>

                    <h3>13.2 Rule 1: Keep It Private</h3>
                    <p>Do not share your agent. Do not put it in group chats. Stranger access = Admin access to your PC.</p>

                    <h3>13.3 Rule 2: Control What It Sees</h3>
                    <p>If your bank is open in a tab, OpenClaw can see it. Close sensitive tabs or use a separate browser profile.</p>

                    <h3>13.4 Rule 3: Think Before Prompting</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Will this expose info?</li>
                        <li>Is this action reversible? (Deleting files)</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>For high stakes, use the <strong>Approval Workflow</strong>: <em>"Before you do anything, tell me your plan and wait for approval."</em></p>
